{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-97a777a9c8a3ade4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "189\t## NABEATs: Noise-Aware Audio Representation Learning\n190\t\n191\t## Abstract\n192\t\n193\tWe propose the concept of noise-aware audio self-supervised learning (SSL), whose goal is to encode audio mixtures while suppressing undesired noise, and present Noise-Aware BEATs (NABEATs) as a BEATs-based realization of this framework.\n194\tAudio SSL models are designed to handle a wide range of audio signals.\n195\tConsequently, under noisy conditions, they cannot effectively focus on the target sounds relevant to a downstream task, resulting in degraded performance.\n196\tTo address this issue, NABEATs is trained to estimate clean BEATs representations from a noisy audio signal with an auxiliary reference noise input.\n197\tThis reference noise enables the model to account for specific noise characteristics at inference time, thereby achieving better generalization across operating environments.\n198\tOur experimental evaluations demonstrate that NABEATs significantly improves performance of various downstream tasks under noisy conditions and also generalizes well to unseen noise types.\n199\t\n200\tIndex Terms— \n201\tself-supervised learning, general-purpose audio representation, noise robustness\n202\t\n203\t## \n204\t1 Introduction\n205\t\n206\t\\Ac\n207\t\n208\tssl models have achieved remarkable success in speech and audio processing.\n209\tThese models learn general-purpose representations from large amounts of unlabeled audio data, enabling transfer to various downstream tasks.\n210\tFor example, speech SSL models [undef, undefa] have demonstrated impressive performance in downstream tasks such as automatic speech recognition, even with a small amount of labeled data or a simple model [undefb].\n211\tBeyond speech, audio SSL models [undefc, undefd, undefe, undeff] have also shown their effectiveness across various downstream tasks including the environmental sound and music domains.\n212\t\n213\tInspired by the success of target sound extraction (TSE) [undefg, undefh, undefi], SSL models that extract target representations from noisy signals have also been explored, especially in the speech domain [undefj, undefk, undefl].\n214\tA representative example is WavLM [undefj], which is trained to predict pseudo labels of the primary speaker’s utterance and ignore both noise and non-primary speech.\n215\tIn addition, speaker-aware variants [undefm, undefn, undefo] have also been proposed to extract the representation of a target speaker specified by a reference enrollment utterance.\n216\tThese methods have made SSL models more effective under real-world noisy conditions and have broadened their applicability.\n217\t\n218\tDespite the progress in noise-robust SSL models for speech, this direction has not yet been explored for general audio SSL models.\n219\tIn addition, audio SSL models are expected to be applicable to a wider variety of downstream tasks than speech SSL models. A method in the spirit of WavLM would thus not be practical, as some types of sounds may need to be preserved for some downstream tasks but suppressed in others.\n220\tFurthermore, unlike speaker-aware SSL, relying on target sound information as reference is unrealistic for some downstream tasks: for example, in audio tagging, which aims to identify the sound class, providing the target sound is essentially equivalent to solving the task.\n221\tIn contrast, even when the target sound is unknown, noise information can often be available, and using noise as a reference is more practical in real-world scenarios.\n222\t\n223\tProjection\n224\t\n225\tEncoder\n226\t\n227\tNA Layer12×12\\timesNABEATs\n228\t\n229\tBEATsOriginalBEATslayersAdditionaltrainablelayerSharedweights\n230\t\n231\t+\n232\t\n233\t𝐱\\mathbf{x}\n234\t\n235\t𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}\n236\t\n237\t𝐧\\mathbf{n}\n238\t\n239\t𝐬\\mathbf{s}\n240\t\n241\tMSE𝐫\\mathbf{r}𝐫^\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\n242\t\n243\tFig. 1: \n244\tOverview of NABEATs. The model estimates clean BEATs representations 𝐫\\mathbf{r} from noisy inputs 𝐱\\mathbf{x} by leveraging an additional reference noise signal 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} for conditional denoising.\n245\t\n246\tIn this paper, we propose the concept of noise-aware audio SSL, whose goal is to encode audio mixtures while suppressing undesired noise similar to a given reference.\n247\tAs a specific realization, we introduce noise-aware BEATs (NABEATs), built upon the widely used and high-performing BEATs [undefc] model.\n248\tNABEATs is trained to estimate clean BEATs representations from noisy audio signals.\n249\tTo achieve this, the model takes as additional input a reference noise signal 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} sharing characteristics with the noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n} in the noisy input (see Fig. 1) and learns to perform conditional denoising.\n250\tWe also introduce denoising BEATs (DBEATs) as a standard denoising baseline, which does not use the reference and is trained similarly to WavLM [undefj].\n251\tIn the experimental evaluation, we demonstrate that both NABEATs and DBEATs significantly improve performance under noisy conditions across various downstream tasks, while NABEATs shows superior generalization to unseen noise.\n252\t\n253\t## \n254\t2 Proposed methods\n255\t\n256\tThe intended usage scenario of NABEATs is similar to that of traditional spectral subtraction [undefp], where a reference noise signal is obtained from noise-only segments, pre-recorded noise at the target location, or a separately placed microphone.\n257\tIn this paper, we focus on the case where the reference noise is obtained from a different time segment from the same recording.\n258\tWe consider this setting to be a practical and reasonable choice, and investigating other conditions is left to future work.\n259\tThe proposed method is expected to handle non-stationary noise better than spectral subtraction, and avoids cascaded systems by operating directly in the representation space.\n260\t\n261\tOur base model, BEATs, is an audio SSL model that performs masked prediction in the discrete token space, where the tokens are obtained from mel-spectrogram patches using an acoustic tokenizer.\n262\tBEATs extracts a representation sequence 𝐫∈ℝL×768\\mathbf{r}\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{L\\times 768} from mel-spectrogram patches through a projection layer and 12 Transformer encoder layers, where LL is the sequence length equal to the number of mel-spectrogram patches.\n263\tBEATs is trained to predict the correct tokens in the masked positions from 𝐫\\mathbf{r}, and the tokenizer is also iteratively updated through distillation from the BEATs model, leading to strong downstream performance.\n264\t\n265\tFigure 1 shows the training framework of NABEATs.\n266\tIt is trained by distillation using the following mean squared error (MSE) loss ℒMSE\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MSE}} between the target representation 𝐫\\mathbf{r} from the frozen original BEATs and its estimate 𝐫^\\hat{\\mathbf{r}} from NABEATs, given by\n267\t\n268\tℒMSE\\displaystyle\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MSE}}\n269\t=1L⋅768​‖𝐫−𝐫^‖F2,\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{L\\cdot 768}\\left\\|\\mathbf{r}-\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\\right\\|_{F}^{2},\n270\t\n271\t(1)\n272\t\n273\t𝐫\\displaystyle\\mathbf{r}\\!\n274\t=BEATs​(𝐬),\\displaystyle=\\!\\mathrm{BEATs}(\\mathbf{s}),\n275\t\n276\t(2)\n277\t\n278\t𝐫^\\displaystyle\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\\!\n279\t=NABEATs​(𝐱,𝐧′),\\displaystyle=\\!\\mathrm{NABEATs}(\\mathbf{x},\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}),\n280\t\n281\t(3)\n282\t\n283\twhere ∥⋅∥F\\|\\cdot\\|_{F} denotes the Frobenius norm. Here, 𝐬\\mathbf{s} and 𝐱=𝐬+𝐧\\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf{s}+\\mathbf{n} denote target sound and noisy input sound, respectively, and\n284\t𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} is a reference noise as introduced in Section 1.\n285\tWe also introduce DBEATs as a standard denoising baseline, which does not use the reference noise:\n286\t\n287\t𝐫^=DBEATs​(𝐱).\\displaystyle\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\\!=\\!\\mathrm{DBEATs}(\\mathbf{x}).\n288\t\n289\t(4)\n290\t\n291\tThe training procedure of DBEATs is identical to that of NABEATs.\n292\t\n293\tFollowing [undefq], we construct DBEATs and NABEATs by inserting additional layers after every encoder layer of the original BEATs, and train only these layers while keeping the original BEATs components frozen. For DBEATs, we employ the following standard Transformer layer as the additional denoising layer:\n294\t\n295\t𝐳𝐱\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\n296\t←𝐳𝐱+MHSA​(RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱)),\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}+\\mathrm{MHSA}(\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}})),\n297\t\n298\t(5)\n299\t\n300\t𝐳𝐱\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\n301\t←𝐳𝐱+FFNSwiGLU​(RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱)),\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}+\\mathrm{FFN}_{\\mathrm{SwiGLU}}(\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}})),\n302\t\n303\t(6)\n304\t\n305\twhere 𝐳𝐱∈ℝL×768\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{L\\times 768} is the representation of the noisy input 𝐱\\mathbf{x} from the previous layer, MHSA denotes multi-head self-attention [undefr], RMSNorm denotes root mean square normalization [undefs], and FFNSwiGLU\\mathrm{FFN}_{\\mathrm{SwiGLU}} denotes a Swish gated linear unit (SwiGLU)-based feed-forward network (FFN) [undeft].\n306\tFor NABEATs, both 𝐱\\mathbf{x} and 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} are passed through the same frozen BEATs components, and the additional noise-aware (NA) layers refine the representation 𝐳𝐱\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}} by leveraging the reference noise representation.\n307\tWe consider two types of NA layers, based on cross-attention (CA) and FiLM [undefu], and refer to the resulting models as NABEATs-CA and NABEATs-FiLM, respectively.\n308\tBoth models replace only 5 with CA or FiLM while keeping the same FFN as in 6.\n309\tSpecifically, NABEATs-CA employs the following CA instead of 5:\n310\t\n311\t𝐳𝐱\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\n312\t←𝐳𝐱+MHCA​(RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱),RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐧′)),\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}+\\mathrm{MHCA}\\!\\left(\\mathrm{RMSNorm}\\left(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\\right),\\mathrm{RMSNorm}\\left(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}\\right)\\right),\n313\t\n314\t(7)\n315\t\n316\twhere MHCA denotes multi-head CA, with the first argument used as the query and the second argument used as the key and value, and 𝐳𝐧′\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}} is the representation of the reference noise 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}.\n317\tNABEATs-FiLM applies the same feature-wise linear modulation to each element of the representation sequence, modifying the ll-th element 𝐳𝐱l\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l} using the averaged reference noise representation 𝐳¯𝐧′\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}:\n318\t\n319\t𝐳¯𝐧′\\displaystyle\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}\n320\t=1L​∑l=1LRMSNorm​(𝐳𝐧′l),\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{L}\\sum_{l=1}^{L}\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}^{l}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}),\n321\t\n322\t(8)\n323\t\n324\t𝜸\\displaystyle\\bm{\\gamma}\n325\t=Affine​(𝐳¯𝐧′)∈ℝ768,\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Affine}(\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{768},\n326\t\n327\t(9)\n328\t\n329\t𝜷\\displaystyle\\bm{\\beta}\n330\t=Affine​(𝐳¯𝐧′)∈ℝ768,\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Affine}(\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{768},\n331\t\n332\t(10)\n333\t\n334\t𝐳𝐱l\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l}\n335\t←𝐳𝐱l+𝜸⊙RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱l)+𝜷,\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l}+\\bm{\\gamma}\\odot\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l})+\\bm{\\beta},\n336\t\n337\t(11)\n338\t\n339\twhere Affine denotes an affine layer, and ⊙\\odot denotes element-wise multiplication.\n340\tNABEATs-FiLM uses only global reference-noise information, whereas NABEATs-CA adaptively aggregates reference information across the sequence.\n341\t\n342\tAnother way to implement noise-aware SSL is to use a cascaded architecture that first performs TSE and then feeds its output into the SSL model.\n343\tHowever, such a cascaded approach tends to be inefficient and incur higher computational cost [undefv]; therefore, in this paper, we focus on an integrated SSL model.\n344\t\n345\t## \n346\t3 Experimental setup\n347\t\n348\tWe conduct two types of evaluations.\n349\tFirst, in Section 4, we evaluate performance on various downstream tasks under simulated noisy conditions using a custom-designed setup.\n350\tFor the reference noise 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} in NABEATs, we use a noise-only segment immediately preceding 𝐧\\mathbf{n} from the same recording, with the same duration, for both NABEATs training and the downstream tasks.\n351\tSecond, in Section 5, we evaluate on the DCASE 2025 Task 2 [undefw], which addresses anomalous sound detection (ASD) for machine condition monitoring.\n352\tIn this task, the dataset contains noisy machine sounds and separately recorded noise-only signals, aligning well with one of the intended applications of our NABEATs framework.\n353\t\n354\tTable 1: \n355\tDatasets used for the training of DBEATs and NABEATs.\n356\tText in parentheses indicates the official split of each dataset used at each stage.\n357\t\n358\tStage\n359\t\n360\tTarget\n361\t\n362\tNoise\n363\t\n364\tTrain\n365\t\n366\tFSD50K (Train)\n367\t\n368\tWHAM! (Train), DEMAND, QUT-NOISE\n369\t\n370\tValid\n371\t\n372\tFSD50K (Valid)\n373\t\n374\tWHAM! (Valid)\n375\t\n376\tTable 2: \n377\tNoise datasets used for downstream evaluation.\n378\tFor WHAM! and MUSDB, we followed the official splits.\n379\tThe CHiME-3 row shows the recording IDs used for each split.\n380\t\n381\tNoise dataset\n382\tTrain\n383\tValid\n384\tTest\n385\t\n386\tWHAM! (seen)\n387\tTrain\n388\tValid\n389\tTest\n390\t\n391\tCHiME-3 (unseen)\n392\t040 & 050\n393\t030\n394\t010 & 020\n395\t\n396\tMUSDB18 (unseen)\n397\tTrain\n398\tValid\n399\tTest\n400\t\n401\tFig. 2: Downstream classification performance under noisy conditions, where mAP is used for FSD50K and accuracy is used for the other tasks.\n402\tEach panel represents one task, with the columns corresponding to different noise conditions and the rows to different models.\n403\t(C) and (N) denote clean and noisy input, respectively.\n404\tAverage scores across six trials with different random seeds are shown, together with 95% confidence intervals.\n405\t“w/ GT” indicates the performance when the reference noise for NABEATs is the ground-truth noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n}.\n406\t\n407\tTable 1 summarizes the datasets for the training of NABEATs and DBEATs.\n408\tWe used FSD50K [undefx] to sample the target sound.\n409\tAlthough BEATs itself is trained on the larger Audioset [undefy], we leave such large-scale training to future work.\n410\tAs the noise dataset, we used WHAM!48kHz [undefz],\n411\tfollowing the official splits.\n412\tIn addition, we used DEMAND [undefaa] and QUT-NOISE [undefab] as training noise datasets.\n413\tAll of these noise datasets contain environmental sounds such as traffic, café, or park noise.\n414\tIn our experiments, all audio signals were resampled to 16 kHz.\n415\tFor both training and validation, we mixed a target sound with a noise signal at random SNRs between -5 and 10 dB.\n416\tDuring training, we randomly cropped or zero-padded the target sound to 10 sec.\n417\t\n418\tFor BEATs, we used the BEATs_iter3.pt checkpoint.111https://github.com/microsoft/unilm/tree/master/beats\n419\tIn the additional layers in DBEATs and NABEATs, we used MHSA and MHCA with 8 heads, respectively.\n420\tFor FFN, we set the hidden size to 2304.\n421\tWe trained both DBEATs and NABEATs for 250 epochs using the AdamW optimizer, a fixed learning rate of 0.0001, and a batch size of 80.\n422\tWe applied an exponential moving average with a decay rate of 0.999 after 20k training steps, and evaluated the model with the best validation loss.\n423\t\n424\t## \n425\t4 Evaluation on various downstream tasks\n426\t\n427\t## \n428\t4.1 Setups\n429\t\n430\tWe conducted evaluation on various downstream tasks according to [undefd, undefe].\n431\tWe trained only a single linear layer on top of the frozen SSL model for downstream classification tasks.\n432\tWe adopted six downstream tasks covering environmental sound, speech, and music domains.\n433\tFor environmental sound classification, we used FSD50K and UrbanSound8K (US8K) [undefac].\n434\tFor speech-related tasks, we used Speech Commands V2 (SPCV2) [undefad] for word classification and CREMA-D (CRM-D) [undefae] for emotion recognition.\n435\tFor music tasks, we used NSynth [undefaf] for instrument family classification and the Surge Pitch Dataset (Surge) [undefag] for pitch classification.\n436\t\n437\tFor US8K, we conducted 10-fold cross-validation following the official splits.\n438\tDuring cross-validation, we randomly divided the non-test folds into training and validation sets with a ratio of 10:1.\n439\tFor the other datasets, we followed the official training, validation, and test splits.\n440\tFollowing [undefd, undefe], for each dataset, audio signals were cropped or zero-padded to the average duration of the dataset. For metrics, we used mean average precision (mAP) for FSD50K, a multi-label task, and accuracy for all other single-label tasks [undefd, undefe].\n441\t\n442\tTable 2 summarizes the noise datasets used to simulate noisy conditions for the above downstream tasks.\n443\tIn addition to WHAM!, which was used to train NABEATs and DBEATs, we used CHiME-3 [undefah] and MUSDB18 [undefai] to evaluate generalization to unseen noise types.\n444\tCHiME-3 contains environmental noise similar to the noise datasets used to train NABEATs and DBEATs, whereas MUSDB18 contains music signals that are substantially different from them.\n445\tWe split CHiME-3 based on the recording IDs.\n446\tFor MUSDB18, we used the official dataset parser222https://github.com/sigsep/sigsep-mus-db to obtain the validation set.\n447\tFor WHAM! and MUSDB18, we excluded signals shorter than 60 sec to ensure that reference noise can be obtained from the same recording across all downstream tasks, while CHiME-3 contains only long recordings.\n448\tFor each split of the downstream datasets, we mixed each sample with a noise signal from the corresponding split of the noise dataset at random SNRs between -5 and 10 dB.\n449\t\n450\tIn the downstream tasks, we fed each representation averaged across the sequence into a linear layer [undefc], which we trained for up to 200 epochs using the Adam optimizer, a learning rate of 0.0003, and a batch size of 200.\n451\tWe used the validation set for early stopping with a patience of 20 epochs.\n452\tWe conducted each evaluation six times with different random seeds, and report the average results with 95% confidence intervals.\n453\t\n454\tFig. 3: t-SNE visualization of the averaged representation of the test set for US8K under the clean condition for BEATs and under the MUSDB18 noise condition for BEATs and NABEATs-CA.\n455\tAll figures have the same axes.\n456\t\n457\t## \n458\t4.2 Results\n459\t\n460\tFigure 2 shows the results across various downstream tasks under noisy conditions, where we used noisy signals as input during both training and inference of the linear head.\n461\tFirst, we can see that performance of the original BEATs degrades significantly under noisy conditions compared with clean conditions in all tasks.\n462\tIn contrast, NABEATs-CA and DBEATs improve the performance in the WHAM! and CHiME-3 noise conditions, except for DBEATs on CRM-D.\n463\tIn the MUSDB18 noise condition, while DBEATs suffers from a large mismatch with the training noise data, NABEATs-CA still improves performance, demonstrating its better generalization to unseen noise conditions.\n464\tFurthermore, by leveraging reference noise, NABEATs-CA achieves better performance than DBEATs even in seen noise conditions in all tasks except SPCV2.\n465\tFrom the comparison between NABEATs-CA and NABEATs-FiLM, we can see that NABEATs-CA performs particularly well on the speech and music tasks and under the MUSDB18 noise condition, indicating that these tasks require more effective handling of time-varying information than environmental sound tasks.\n466\tLastly, to investigate the behavior of NABEATs, we evaluated NABEATs-CA w/ GT, which uses the ground-truth noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n} as the reference noise.\n467\tIt yields a slight but consistent performance improvement over NABEATs-CA, which can be regarded as a reasonable upper-bound performance.\n468\tSince NABEATs is not trained using the ground-truth noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n} as the reference noise, this result also shows the robustness of NABEATs to a different reference noise segment.\n469\t\n470\tTable 3 shows the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) between the clean representation sequences 𝐫\\mathbf{r} and their estimates 𝐫^\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}, highlighting the substantial improvement by the proposed methods.\n471\tWe note that DBEATs improves SNR even on CRM-D, despite degrading downstream performance, which indicates a potential mismatch between downstream performance and the MSE objective.\n472\tWe leave investigation of better training objectives to future work.\n473\t\n474\tFigure 3 shows t-SNE [undefaj] visualizations of the averaged representation of the test set for US8K under the clean condition for BEATs and under the MUSDB18 noise condition for BEATs and NABEATs-CA.\n475\tThe original BEATs representations are well separated across classes in the clean condition, but become mixed under the noisy condition.\n476\tIn contrast, NABEATs-CA maintains better class separability under noisy conditions, leading to better downstream performance and SNR.\n477\t\n478\tTable 3: \n479\tSNR [dB] results between the clean and estimated representation sequences.\n480\tW and M indicate WHAM! and MUSDB18 noise conditions, respectively.\n481\t\n482\tFSD50K\n483\tCRM-D\n484\tNSynth\n485\t\n486\tW\n487\tM\n488\tW\n489\tM\n490\tW\n491\tM\n492\t\n493\tBEATs\n494\t1.951.95\n495\t1.301.30\n496\t3.193.19\n497\t2.442.44\n498\t0.240.24\n499\t−0.02-0.02\n500\t\n501\tDBEATs\n502\t7.457.45\n503\t3.253.25\n504\t3.823.82\n505\t2.182.18\n506\t4.444.44\n507\t1.421.42\n508\t\n509\tNABEATs-CA\n510\t7.567.56\n511\t5.395.39\n512\t5.475.47\n513\t4.054.05\n514\t4.504.50\n515\t3.193.19\n516\t\n517\t## \n518\t5 Evaluation on DCASE 2025 Task 2\n519\t\n520\tWe also conducted evaluation using the DCASE 2025 Task 2 dataset [undefw], compiled from [undefak, undefal, undefam].\n521\tThis dataset contains 15 machine types, each with 1000 normal training samples and 200 test samples including normal and anomalous samples.\n522\tNine of the 15 machine types include 100 noise-only signals as supplementary data, and we restrict our experiments to these machine types.\n523\t\n524\tFollowing [undefan], without using any additional neural network, we simply calculated the anomaly score based on the distance between the representation of the test sample and those of the normal training samples, where we averaged the representation across the sequence.\n525\tWe used the standard anomaly score calculation method which uses SMOTE oversampling [undefao] to mitigate the class imbalance in the training set and then calculates the cosine distance to the nearest training sample [undefap, undefaq].\n526\tFor NABEATs, we selected a reference noise sample from the supplementary data with minimum distance to the input noisy machine sound in the original BEATs representation.\n527\t\n528\tAs the evaluation metric, we used the official task score based on the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve [undefw] and report its harmonic mean across the nine machine types.\n529\t\n530\tThe evaluation scores on DCASE 2025 Task 2 are 54.57 for BEATs, 55.76 for DBEATs, and 56.15 for NABEATs-CA.\n531\tThis further verifies the effectiveness of the proposed methods even when the reference noise is not the segment immediately preceding 𝐧\\mathbf{n}, and also demonstrates their effectiveness on a public benchmark dataset.\n532\t\n533\t## \n534\t6 Conclusion\n535\t\n536\tIn this paper, we explored the concept of noise-aware audio SSL and proposed NABEATs as a realization of this framework based on BEATs.\n537\tWhile the standard denoising baseline DBEATs is simply trained to estimate clean representations from noisy signals, NABEATs additionally takes a reference noise as input and is trained to suppress the corresponding noise information.\n538\tOur experiments showed that, while both methods significantly improve performance under noisy conditions, NABEATs outperforms DBEATs in both seen and unseen noise conditions, highlighting the benefit of using a reference noise to make the model noise-aware.\n539\tFuture work includes investigating other reference noise settings, better training objectives for downstream tasks, and larger-scale training.\n540\t\n541\t## \n542\t7 References\n543\t\n544\t## References\n545\t\n546\t- \n547\t[undef]\n548\tWei-Ning Hsu et al.\n549\t\n550\t“HuBERT: Self-supervised speech representation learning by masked prediction of hidden units”\n551\t\n552\tIn IEEE/ACM TASLP 29, 2021, pp. 3451–3460\n553\t\n554\t- \n555\t[undefa]\n556\tAlexei Baevski, Yuhao Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed and Michael Auli\n557\t\n558\t“wav2vec 2.0: A Framework for Self-Supervised Learning of Speech Representations”\n559\t\n560\tIn Proc. NeurIPS 33, 2020, pp. 12449–12460\n561\t\n562\tURL: https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper_files/paper/2020/file/92d1e1eb1cd6f9fba3227870bb6d7f07-Paper.pdf\n563\t\n564\t- \n565\t[undefb]\n566\tShu-wen Yang et al.\n567\t\n568\t“SUPERB: Speech Processing Universal PERformance Benchmark”\n569\t\n570\tIn Proc. Interspeech, 2021, pp. 1194–1198\n571\t\n572\tDOI: 10.21437/Interspeech.2021-1775\n573\t\n574\t- \n575\t[undefc]\n576\tSanyuan Chen et al.\n577\t\n578\t“BEATs: Audio Pre-Training with Acoustic Tokenizers”\n579\t\n580\tIn Proc. ICML, 2023, pp. 5178–5193\n581\t\n582\t- \n583\t[undefd]\n584\tDaisuke Niizumi et al.\n585\t\n586\t“BYOL for Audio: Exploring pre-trained general-purpose audio representations”\n587\t\n588\tIn IEEE/ACM TASLP 31, 2022, pp. 137–151\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "0bdf5c4c-ff4a-43f3-90c9-856cf584af91", "uuid": "66c14cde-d9a2-46aa-8037-2630dbede5e3", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T12:01:36.142Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/nabeats_text.txt", "content": "## NABEATs: Noise-Aware Audio Representation Learning\n\n## Abstract\n\nWe propose the concept of noise-aware audio self-supervised learning (SSL), whose goal is to encode audio mixtures while suppressing undesired noise, and present Noise-Aware BEATs (NABEATs) as a BEATs-based realization of this framework.\nAudio SSL models are designed to handle a wide range of audio signals.\nConsequently, under noisy conditions, they cannot effectively focus on the target sounds relevant to a downstream task, resulting in degraded performance.\nTo address this issue, NABEATs is trained to estimate clean BEATs representations from a noisy audio signal with an auxiliary reference noise input.\nThis reference noise enables the model to account for specific noise characteristics at inference time, thereby achieving better generalization across operating environments.\nOur experimental evaluations demonstrate that NABEATs significantly improves performance of various downstream tasks under noisy conditions and also generalizes well to unseen noise types.\n\nIndex Terms— \nself-supervised learning, general-purpose audio representation, noise robustness\n\n## \n1 Introduction\n\n\\Ac\n\nssl models have achieved remarkable success in speech and audio processing.\nThese models learn general-purpose representations from large amounts of unlabeled audio data, enabling transfer to various downstream tasks.\nFor example, speech SSL models [undef, undefa] have demonstrated impressive performance in downstream tasks such as automatic speech recognition, even with a small amount of labeled data or a simple model [undefb].\nBeyond speech, audio SSL models [undefc, undefd, undefe, undeff] have also shown their effectiveness across various downstream tasks including the environmental sound and music domains.\n\nInspired by the success of target sound extraction (TSE) [undefg, undefh, undefi], SSL models that extract target representations from noisy signals have also been explored, especially in the speech domain [undefj, undefk, undefl].\nA representative example is WavLM [undefj], which is trained to predict pseudo labels of the primary speaker’s utterance and ignore both noise and non-primary speech.\nIn addition, speaker-aware variants [undefm, undefn, undefo] have also been proposed to extract the representation of a target speaker specified by a reference enrollment utterance.\nThese methods have made SSL models more effective under real-world noisy conditions and have broadened their applicability.\n\nDespite the progress in noise-robust SSL models for speech, this direction has not yet been explored for general audio SSL models.\nIn addition, audio SSL models are expected to be applicable to a wider variety of downstream tasks than speech SSL models. A method in the spirit of WavLM would thus not be practical, as some types of sounds may need to be preserved for some downstream tasks but suppressed in others.\nFurthermore, unlike speaker-aware SSL, relying on target sound information as reference is unrealistic for some downstream tasks: for example, in audio tagging, which aims to identify the sound class, providing the target sound is essentially equivalent to solving the task.\nIn contrast, even when the target sound is unknown, noise information can often be available, and using noise as a reference is more practical in real-world scenarios.\n\nProjection\n\nEncoder\n\nNA Layer12×12\\timesNABEATs\n\nBEATsOriginalBEATslayersAdditionaltrainablelayerSharedweights\n\n+\n\n𝐱\\mathbf{x}\n\n𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}\n\n𝐧\\mathbf{n}\n\n𝐬\\mathbf{s}\n\nMSE𝐫\\mathbf{r}𝐫^\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\n\nFig. 1: \nOverview of NABEATs. The model estimates clean BEATs representations 𝐫\\mathbf{r} from noisy inputs 𝐱\\mathbf{x} by leveraging an additional reference noise signal 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} for conditional denoising.\n\nIn this paper, we propose the concept of noise-aware audio SSL, whose goal is to encode audio mixtures while suppressing undesired noise similar to a given reference.\nAs a specific realization, we introduce noise-aware BEATs (NABEATs), built upon the widely used and high-performing BEATs [undefc] model.\nNABEATs is trained to estimate clean BEATs representations from noisy audio signals.\nTo achieve this, the model takes as additional input a reference noise signal 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} sharing characteristics with the noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n} in the noisy input (see Fig. 1) and learns to perform conditional denoising.\nWe also introduce denoising BEATs (DBEATs) as a standard denoising baseline, which does not use the reference and is trained similarly to WavLM [undefj].\nIn the experimental evaluation, we demonstrate that both NABEATs and DBEATs significantly improve performance under noisy conditions across various downstream tasks, while NABEATs shows superior generalization to unseen noise.\n\n## \n2 Proposed methods\n\nThe intended usage scenario of NABEATs is similar to that of traditional spectral subtraction [undefp], where a reference noise signal is obtained from noise-only segments, pre-recorded noise at the target location, or a separately placed microphone.\nIn this paper, we focus on the case where the reference noise is obtained from a different time segment from the same recording.\nWe consider this setting to be a practical and reasonable choice, and investigating other conditions is left to future work.\nThe proposed method is expected to handle non-stationary noise better than spectral subtraction, and avoids cascaded systems by operating directly in the representation space.\n\nOur base model, BEATs, is an audio SSL model that performs masked prediction in the discrete token space, where the tokens are obtained from mel-spectrogram patches using an acoustic tokenizer.\nBEATs extracts a representation sequence 𝐫∈ℝL×768\\mathbf{r}\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{L\\times 768} from mel-spectrogram patches through a projection layer and 12 Transformer encoder layers, where LL is the sequence length equal to the number of mel-spectrogram patches.\nBEATs is trained to predict the correct tokens in the masked positions from 𝐫\\mathbf{r}, and the tokenizer is also iteratively updated through distillation from the BEATs model, leading to strong downstream performance.\n\nFigure 1 shows the training framework of NABEATs.\nIt is trained by distillation using the following mean squared error (MSE) loss ℒMSE\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MSE}} between the target representation 𝐫\\mathbf{r} from the frozen original BEATs and its estimate 𝐫^\\hat{\\mathbf{r}} from NABEATs, given by\n\nℒMSE\\displaystyle\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MSE}}\n=1L⋅768​‖𝐫−𝐫^‖F2,\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{L\\cdot 768}\\left\\|\\mathbf{r}-\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\\right\\|_{F}^{2},\n\n(1)\n\n𝐫\\displaystyle\\mathbf{r}\\!\n=BEATs​(𝐬),\\displaystyle=\\!\\mathrm{BEATs}(\\mathbf{s}),\n\n(2)\n\n𝐫^\\displaystyle\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\\!\n=NABEATs​(𝐱,𝐧′),\\displaystyle=\\!\\mathrm{NABEATs}(\\mathbf{x},\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}),\n\n(3)\n\nwhere ∥⋅∥F\\|\\cdot\\|_{F} denotes the Frobenius norm. Here, 𝐬\\mathbf{s} and 𝐱=𝐬+𝐧\\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf{s}+\\mathbf{n} denote target sound and noisy input sound, respectively, and\n𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} is a reference noise as introduced in Section 1.\nWe also introduce DBEATs as a standard denoising baseline, which does not use the reference noise:\n\n𝐫^=DBEATs​(𝐱).\\displaystyle\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}\\!=\\!\\mathrm{DBEATs}(\\mathbf{x}).\n\n(4)\n\nThe training procedure of DBEATs is identical to that of NABEATs.\n\nFollowing [undefq], we construct DBEATs and NABEATs by inserting additional layers after every encoder layer of the original BEATs, and train only these layers while keeping the original BEATs components frozen. For DBEATs, we employ the following standard Transformer layer as the additional denoising layer:\n\n𝐳𝐱\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\n←𝐳𝐱+MHSA​(RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱)),\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}+\\mathrm{MHSA}(\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}})),\n\n(5)\n\n𝐳𝐱\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\n←𝐳𝐱+FFNSwiGLU​(RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱)),\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}+\\mathrm{FFN}_{\\mathrm{SwiGLU}}(\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}})),\n\n(6)\n\nwhere 𝐳𝐱∈ℝL×768\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{L\\times 768} is the representation of the noisy input 𝐱\\mathbf{x} from the previous layer, MHSA denotes multi-head self-attention [undefr], RMSNorm denotes root mean square normalization [undefs], and FFNSwiGLU\\mathrm{FFN}_{\\mathrm{SwiGLU}} denotes a Swish gated linear unit (SwiGLU)-based feed-forward network (FFN) [undeft].\nFor NABEATs, both 𝐱\\mathbf{x} and 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} are passed through the same frozen BEATs components, and the additional noise-aware (NA) layers refine the representation 𝐳𝐱\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}} by leveraging the reference noise representation.\nWe consider two types of NA layers, based on cross-attention (CA) and FiLM [undefu], and refer to the resulting models as NABEATs-CA and NABEATs-FiLM, respectively.\nBoth models replace only 5 with CA or FiLM while keeping the same FFN as in 6.\nSpecifically, NABEATs-CA employs the following CA instead of 5:\n\n𝐳𝐱\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\n←𝐳𝐱+MHCA​(RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱),RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐧′)),\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}+\\mathrm{MHCA}\\!\\left(\\mathrm{RMSNorm}\\left(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}\\right),\\mathrm{RMSNorm}\\left(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}\\right)\\right),\n\n(7)\n\nwhere MHCA denotes multi-head CA, with the first argument used as the query and the second argument used as the key and value, and 𝐳𝐧′\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}} is the representation of the reference noise 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}.\nNABEATs-FiLM applies the same feature-wise linear modulation to each element of the representation sequence, modifying the ll-th element 𝐳𝐱l\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l} using the averaged reference noise representation 𝐳¯𝐧′\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}:\n\n𝐳¯𝐧′\\displaystyle\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}\n=1L​∑l=1LRMSNorm​(𝐳𝐧′l),\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{L}\\sum_{l=1}^{L}\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}^{l}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}}),\n\n(8)\n\n𝜸\\displaystyle\\bm{\\gamma}\n=Affine​(𝐳¯𝐧′)∈ℝ768,\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Affine}(\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{768},\n\n(9)\n\n𝜷\\displaystyle\\bm{\\beta}\n=Affine​(𝐳¯𝐧′)∈ℝ768,\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Affine}(\\bar{\\mathbf{z}}_{\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime}})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{768},\n\n(10)\n\n𝐳𝐱l\\displaystyle\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l}\n←𝐳𝐱l+𝜸⊙RMSNorm​(𝐳𝐱l)+𝜷,\\displaystyle\\xleftarrow{}\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l}+\\bm{\\gamma}\\odot\\mathrm{RMSNorm}(\\mathbf{z}_{\\mathbf{x}}^{l})+\\bm{\\beta},\n\n(11)\n\nwhere Affine denotes an affine layer, and ⊙\\odot denotes element-wise multiplication.\nNABEATs-FiLM uses only global reference-noise information, whereas NABEATs-CA adaptively aggregates reference information across the sequence.\n\nAnother way to implement noise-aware SSL is to use a cascaded architecture that first performs TSE and then feeds its output into the SSL model.\nHowever, such a cascaded approach tends to be inefficient and incur higher computational cost [undefv]; therefore, in this paper, we focus on an integrated SSL model.\n\n## \n3 Experimental setup\n\nWe conduct two types of evaluations.\nFirst, in Section 4, we evaluate performance on various downstream tasks under simulated noisy conditions using a custom-designed setup.\nFor the reference noise 𝐧′\\mathbf{n}^{\\prime} in NABEATs, we use a noise-only segment immediately preceding 𝐧\\mathbf{n} from the same recording, with the same duration, for both NABEATs training and the downstream tasks.\nSecond, in Section 5, we evaluate on the DCASE 2025 Task 2 [undefw], which addresses anomalous sound detection (ASD) for machine condition monitoring.\nIn this task, the dataset contains noisy machine sounds and separately recorded noise-only signals, aligning well with one of the intended applications of our NABEATs framework.\n\nTable 1: \nDatasets used for the training of DBEATs and NABEATs.\nText in parentheses indicates the official split of each dataset used at each stage.\n\nStage\n\nTarget\n\nNoise\n\nTrain\n\nFSD50K (Train)\n\nWHAM! (Train), DEMAND, QUT-NOISE\n\nValid\n\nFSD50K (Valid)\n\nWHAM! (Valid)\n\nTable 2: \nNoise datasets used for downstream evaluation.\nFor WHAM! and MUSDB, we followed the official splits.\nThe CHiME-3 row shows the recording IDs used for each split.\n\nNoise dataset\nTrain\nValid\nTest\n\nWHAM! (seen)\nTrain\nValid\nTest\n\nCHiME-3 (unseen)\n040 & 050\n030\n010 & 020\n\nMUSDB18 (unseen)\nTrain\nValid\nTest\n\nFig. 2: Downstream classification performance under noisy conditions, where mAP is used for FSD50K and accuracy is used for the other tasks.\nEach panel represents one task, with the columns corresponding to different noise conditions and the rows to different models.\n(C) and (N) denote clean and noisy input, respectively.\nAverage scores across six trials with different random seeds are shown, together with 95% confidence intervals.\n“w/ GT” indicates the performance when the reference noise for NABEATs is the ground-truth noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n}.\n\nTable 1 summarizes the datasets for the training of NABEATs and DBEATs.\nWe used FSD50K [undefx] to sample the target sound.\nAlthough BEATs itself is trained on the larger Audioset [undefy], we leave such large-scale training to future work.\nAs the noise dataset, we used WHAM!48kHz [undefz],\nfollowing the official splits.\nIn addition, we used DEMAND [undefaa] and QUT-NOISE [undefab] as training noise datasets.\nAll of these noise datasets contain environmental sounds such as traffic, café, or park noise.\nIn our experiments, all audio signals were resampled to 16 kHz.\nFor both training and validation, we mixed a target sound with a noise signal at random SNRs between -5 and 10 dB.\nDuring training, we randomly cropped or zero-padded the target sound to 10 sec.\n\nFor BEATs, we used the BEATs_iter3.pt checkpoint.111https://github.com/microsoft/unilm/tree/master/beats\nIn the additional layers in DBEATs and NABEATs, we used MHSA and MHCA with 8 heads, respectively.\nFor FFN, we set the hidden size to 2304.\nWe trained both DBEATs and NABEATs for 250 epochs using the AdamW optimizer, a fixed learning rate of 0.0001, and a batch size of 80.\nWe applied an exponential moving average with a decay rate of 0.999 after 20k training steps, and evaluated the model with the best validation loss.\n\n## \n4 Evaluation on various downstream tasks\n\n## \n4.1 Setups\n\nWe conducted evaluation on various downstream tasks according to [undefd, undefe].\nWe trained only a single linear layer on top of the frozen SSL model for downstream classification tasks.\nWe adopted six downstream tasks covering environmental sound, speech, and music domains.\nFor environmental sound classification, we used FSD50K and UrbanSound8K (US8K) [undefac].\nFor speech-related tasks, we used Speech Commands V2 (SPCV2) [undefad] for word classification and CREMA-D (CRM-D) [undefae] for emotion recognition.\nFor music tasks, we used NSynth [undefaf] for instrument family classification and the Surge Pitch Dataset (Surge) [undefag] for pitch classification.\n\nFor US8K, we conducted 10-fold cross-validation following the official splits.\nDuring cross-validation, we randomly divided the non-test folds into training and validation sets with a ratio of 10:1.\nFor the other datasets, we followed the official training, validation, and test splits.\nFollowing [undefd, undefe], for each dataset, audio signals were cropped or zero-padded to the average duration of the dataset. For metrics, we used mean average precision (mAP) for FSD50K, a multi-label task, and accuracy for all other single-label tasks [undefd, undefe].\n\nTable 2 summarizes the noise datasets used to simulate noisy conditions for the above downstream tasks.\nIn addition to WHAM!, which was used to train NABEATs and DBEATs, we used CHiME-3 [undefah] and MUSDB18 [undefai] to evaluate generalization to unseen noise types.\nCHiME-3 contains environmental noise similar to the noise datasets used to train NABEATs and DBEATs, whereas MUSDB18 contains music signals that are substantially different from them.\nWe split CHiME-3 based on the recording IDs.\nFor MUSDB18, we used the official dataset parser222https://github.com/sigsep/sigsep-mus-db to obtain the validation set.\nFor WHAM! and MUSDB18, we excluded signals shorter than 60 sec to ensure that reference noise can be obtained from the same recording across all downstream tasks, while CHiME-3 contains only long recordings.\nFor each split of the downstream datasets, we mixed each sample with a noise signal from the corresponding split of the noise dataset at random SNRs between -5 and 10 dB.\n\nIn the downstream tasks, we fed each representation averaged across the sequence into a linear layer [undefc], which we trained for up to 200 epochs using the Adam optimizer, a learning rate of 0.0003, and a batch size of 200.\nWe used the validation set for early stopping with a patience of 20 epochs.\nWe conducted each evaluation six times with different random seeds, and report the average results with 95% confidence intervals.\n\nFig. 3: t-SNE visualization of the averaged representation of the test set for US8K under the clean condition for BEATs and under the MUSDB18 noise condition for BEATs and NABEATs-CA.\nAll figures have the same axes.\n\n## \n4.2 Results\n\nFigure 2 shows the results across various downstream tasks under noisy conditions, where we used noisy signals as input during both training and inference of the linear head.\nFirst, we can see that performance of the original BEATs degrades significantly under noisy conditions compared with clean conditions in all tasks.\nIn contrast, NABEATs-CA and DBEATs improve the performance in the WHAM! and CHiME-3 noise conditions, except for DBEATs on CRM-D.\nIn the MUSDB18 noise condition, while DBEATs suffers from a large mismatch with the training noise data, NABEATs-CA still improves performance, demonstrating its better generalization to unseen noise conditions.\nFurthermore, by leveraging reference noise, NABEATs-CA achieves better performance than DBEATs even in seen noise conditions in all tasks except SPCV2.\nFrom the comparison between NABEATs-CA and NABEATs-FiLM, we can see that NABEATs-CA performs particularly well on the speech and music tasks and under the MUSDB18 noise condition, indicating that these tasks require more effective handling of time-varying information than environmental sound tasks.\nLastly, to investigate the behavior of NABEATs, we evaluated NABEATs-CA w/ GT, which uses the ground-truth noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n} as the reference noise.\nIt yields a slight but consistent performance improvement over NABEATs-CA, which can be regarded as a reasonable upper-bound performance.\nSince NABEATs is not trained using the ground-truth noise 𝐧\\mathbf{n} as the reference noise, this result also shows the robustness of NABEATs to a different reference noise segment.\n\nTable 3 shows the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) between the clean representation sequences 𝐫\\mathbf{r} and their estimates 𝐫^\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}, highlighting the substantial improvement by the proposed methods.\nWe note that DBEATs improves SNR even on CRM-D, despite degrading downstream performance, which indicates a potential mismatch between downstream performance and the MSE objective.\nWe leave investigation of better training objectives to future work.\n\nFigure 3 shows t-SNE [undefaj] visualizations of the averaged representation of the test set for US8K under the clean condition for BEATs and under the MUSDB18 noise condition for BEATs and NABEATs-CA.\nThe original BEATs representations are well separated across classes in the clean condition, but become mixed under the noisy condition.\nIn contrast, NABEATs-CA maintains better class separability under noisy conditions, leading to better downstream performance and SNR.\n\nTable 3: \nSNR [dB] results between the clean and estimated representation sequences.\nW and M indicate WHAM! and MUSDB18 noise conditions, respectively.\n\nFSD50K\nCRM-D\nNSynth\n\nW\nM\nW\nM\nW\nM\n\nBEATs\n1.951.95\n1.301.30\n3.193.19\n2.442.44\n0.240.24\n−0.02-0.02\n\nDBEATs\n7.457.45\n3.253.25\n3.823.82\n2.182.18\n4.444.44\n1.421.42\n\nNABEATs-CA\n7.567.56\n5.395.39\n5.475.47\n4.054.05\n4.504.50\n3.193.19\n\n## \n5 Evaluation on DCASE 2025 Task 2\n\nWe also conducted evaluation using the DCASE 2025 Task 2 dataset [undefw], compiled from [undefak, undefal, undefam].\nThis dataset contains 15 machine types, each with 1000 normal training samples and 200 test samples including normal and anomalous samples.\nNine of the 15 machine types include 100 noise-only signals as supplementary data, and we restrict our experiments to these machine types.\n\nFollowing [undefan], without using any additional neural network, we simply calculated the anomaly score based on the distance between the representation of the test sample and those of the normal training samples, where we averaged the representation across the sequence.\nWe used the standard anomaly score calculation method which uses SMOTE oversampling [undefao] to mitigate the class imbalance in the training set and then calculates the cosine distance to the nearest training sample [undefap, undefaq].\nFor NABEATs, we selected a reference noise sample from the supplementary data with minimum distance to the input noisy machine sound in the original BEATs representation.\n\nAs the evaluation metric, we used the official task score based on the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve [undefw] and report its harmonic mean across the nine machine types.\n\nThe evaluation scores on DCASE 2025 Task 2 are 54.57 for BEATs, 55.76 for DBEATs, and 56.15 for NABEATs-CA.\nThis further verifies the effectiveness of the proposed methods even when the reference noise is not the segment immediately preceding 𝐧\\mathbf{n}, and also demonstrates their effectiveness on a public benchmark dataset.\n\n## \n6 Conclusion\n\nIn this paper, we explored the concept of noise-aware audio SSL and proposed NABEATs as a realization of this framework based on BEATs.\nWhile the standard denoising baseline DBEATs is simply trained to estimate clean representations from noisy signals, NABEATs additionally takes a reference noise as input and is trained to suppress the corresponding noise information.\nOur experiments showed that, while both methods significantly improve performance under noisy conditions, NABEATs outperforms DBEATs in both seen and unseen noise conditions, highlighting the benefit of using a reference noise to make the model noise-aware.\nFuture work includes investigating other reference noise settings, better training objectives for downstream tasks, and larger-scale training.\n\n## \n7 References\n\n## References\n\n- \n[undef]\nWei-Ning Hsu et al.\n\n“HuBERT: Self-supervised speech representation learning by masked prediction of hidden units”\n\nIn IEEE/ACM TASLP 29, 2021, pp. 3451–3460\n\n- \n[undefa]\nAlexei Baevski, Yuhao Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed and Michael Au